  "prompt": "What are some examples of Russian superstitions?",
  "response": "Here are some examples of Russian superstitions:\n\n1. Sitting at the corner of a table\n- Believed to bring bad luck or prevent marriage for unmarried people\n\n2. Whistling indoors\n- Considered bad luck and thought to cause financial loss\n\n3. Avoiding empty bottles on the table\n- Seen as a sign of bad luck or impending poverty\n\n4. Not shaking hands across a threshold\n- Considered bad luck and believed to cause conflict\n\n5. Spilling salt\n- Thought to bring bad fortune, can be countered by throwing salt over left shoulder\n\n6. Even number of flowers\n- Used only at funerals; giving even-numbered flowers is considered unlucky\n\n7. Avoiding eye contact during a toast\n- Believed to bring bad luck or misfortune\n\n8. Not returning home for forgotten items\n- Thought to bring bad luck if you immediately return home after leaving\n\n9. Avoiding discussing future plans\n- Superstitious people prefer not to talk about future success to prevent jinxing it\n\n10. Breaking a mirror\n- Believed to bring seven years of bad luck, similar to Western superstition\n\nThese superstitions reflect a mix of cultural beliefs, folklore, and traditional practices in Russian society.",
